		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Mon, Feb 5th 7:18 PM 2001 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=6&mid=98037751919558&num=4&page=&post=1&replyto=9814005034072"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=9814005034072></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=12186"><span id=>Jonze</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>16 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>There is post by PraetorFenix that explains this as well.&nbsp;&nbsp;This is my take of the stuff from lvl 15 paladin.  Anyways, I already typed it by the time I noticed Praetor's post.<br><br>I read this post about max damage: <br><a href="http://eqforge.com/forums/Forum16/HTML/008833.html" target=_new>http://eqforge.com/forums/Forum16/HTML/008833.html</a><br><br>It said that max damage is: <br>MAX = [((Weapon Skill + Strength)/100) * (DMG)) + (Level Damage Bonus)] <br><br>Level Damage Bonus = (Level - 25)/3 <br><br>I didn't care as much about the formulas, but I was intersted in the relationship of strength and weapon skill and the role they played.  I find the formulas to be pretty accurate, but not right on the money. It is really geared for people lvl 30 or above.<br><br>That article suggests that one's weapon skill + strength are determining factors in damage. The weapons damage is a no brainer in its importance. <br><br>So for example a level 15 paladin like me has a Blackened Iron Bastard sword (20/48). My skill is maxed (5+5*lvl) at 80. My strength is 102. <br><br>Max = ((102+80)/100)*20)+0 <br>Max = 36 <br><br>But thats funny, I usually hit for 29. Well since I'm under level 20, I have a twink cap at 29. I can't hit harder until I reach level 20. <br><br>My 1hs is a forged long sword and my 1HB is the Shining Star.  Hmmm, lets see what do I use? The Blackened Iron Bastard sword.  The other ones work, but are used more to up weapon skill.<br><br>This is what I've been doing.  I carry around my blackend sword at all times.  If I'm working on skill level, I'll switch out my 2HS for the round shield and long sword.  But if I find my self getting in trouble, then I whip out big daddy and let him take care of business:)<br><br>I love that sword, it was a gift to me when I formed our guild. But the damage it can do is very misleading. Its delay is so slow, what happens if I miss. Or if I miss twice? Some mobs are just more agile or dexterous than other mobs.  Their level compared to mine is also a factor.  A question is, if I miss 30% of the time with the long delay two hander, will I also miss 30% of the time with a short delay weapon? <br><br>If I do, then the answer is pretty easy, I would chose whatever weapon gave me the most damage in a given time period.<br><br>I have no idea of how people determine damage per second. So I can do an easier example.  Lets use my Blackened Iron Bastard sword and my Shining Star of Light.  Using the above formula, I expect to get 11 damage max from the Shining star of Light and 29 damage max from the sword.  Lets assume that I will hit max of both and connect 70% of the time.<br><br>Since the Shining Star is twice as fast as the Blackened bastard sword, it will hit 14 times out of 20 swings, while the bastard sword hits 7 times out of 10 swings in the same time period.<br><br>Shining Star total dam = 14*11 = 154<br>Blackend Sword tot dam = 7*29 = 203<br><br>This doesn't take into account bash.  Lets say, I bash for 6, hitting 70% of the time, and bash is used once every 3 swings of the shining star, we can assume 3-4 bashes at 6dmg.  That helps some, but not enough.<br><br>I find from my experience, that my blackened sword is just better while soloing and often during grouping. Althougth the numbers I'm using does not use hits that are below max damage and assumes that the hit/miss ratio is equal, the max damage of those weapons are accurate.  So don't flame me cause of the numbers, its just speculation.<br><br>In groups I find that sometimes, the blackened sword isn't too effective.  Since groups take on bigger and badder things than soloing, I find when I miss, I'm missing big.  Sometimes 3 times in a row.  If fighting trains or longer fights, then its works good, but if the fight is short and quick, I often find that I really didn't contribute enough damage.<br></p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>This is the way, grasshopper.</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td class=mhback align=right><span class=mh id=fs8><a class=mh href=/db/classes.html?class=6><img src=/shared/root_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Up" width=17 height=11> Thread Index</a> |  <a class=mh href=/db/classes.html?class=6&post=1><img src=/shared/new_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="New" width=17 height=11> New Subject</a> | <a class=mh href=/db/classes.html?class=6&mid=98037751919558&num=4&page=&post=1&mid=98037751919558><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply" width=17 height=11> Reply to Thread</a></span></td></tr><tr><td><table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 class=mform><tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>4 Posts [ <a href="/fsearch.html?base=class6">Search Forums</a> ]</nobr></td></tr></table>&nbsp;</td></tr>
